This photo was used to illustrate an article on Glendinning's enlistment in the June, 1918 number of The Recruiter's Bulletin, a publication of the U.S. Marines:
&quot;POPULAR NEW YORK ACTOR ENLISTS Ernest Glendinning one of the the most popular actors and conceded  by dramatic critics to be the fore most player of juvenile roles in  America retired from the stage for the period of the war when he joined the Marines at the New York recruiting station and left for Paris Island May 21.  Mr Glendinning, whose theatrical career covers a period of 17 years, had a long series of triumphs on the stage leading up to his last appearance in New York as leading man of the &quot;Gypsy Trail&quot;.  He was in the employ of the Standard Oil Company when in 1901 he was engaged for a minor role in &quot;Mice and Men&quot;, the company of which Miss Annie Russell was the star. He afterwards played the leading juvenile parts for the Alcazar Stock Company of San Francisco during the years 1905 to 1909.  Broadway critics were united in their praise of his work in &quot;Baby Mine&quot;,  the play in which he supported Francis Wilson in 1910, and for the three years prior to his engagement in the &quot;Gypsy Trail&quot; he played the leading role in &quot;Experience&quot;. Mr Glendinning was born in England 34 years ago He is a son of the late John Glendinning, in his day one of the best known actors on the English speaking stage.&quot;
<a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=XjtHAQAAIAAJ&amp;pg=RA1-PA51&amp;lpg=RA1-PA51&amp;dq=ernest+glendinning+marines&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=o345vgc1qC&amp;sig=jawlqHWWbqfAr3cL7CFd8LjbD_g&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=0ahUKEwiihIXu9ofOAhVTzWMKHco0BwkQ6AEIQDAF#v=onepage&amp;q=ernest%20glendinning%20marines&amp;f=false" rel="nofollow">books.google.com/books?id=XjtHAQAAIAAJ&amp;pg=RA1-PA51&am...</a>

